		          Further Notes
		*********************************

1.	Product id numbers were used for categories such as yogurt to group
   together similar types of a single brand (e.g. all fruit variations of 
   Brand A yogurt)

2.	DPR, REG, SCVAL, and MCVAL are all in dollars.

3.	The daily or 'deal' price refers to the price on the shelves which 
   was actually paid by the consumers, prior to any coupons. 

4.	In the original Household Purchase History files there were
   observations which had a non-zero value for SCUNITS (or MCUNITS) but a
   value of zero for SCVAL (or MCVAL).  If such were the case on a given day,
   SCIND (or MCIND) was given a value of 1 and SCVAL (or MCVAL) was given
   a value of -999.

5.	Within a product id in the dry detergent category, certain upc's 
   corresponded to a version of that product for which the manufacturer
   suggested a cut in the regular price, and this suggested price was
   advertised on the label of the product.  The variable CUT gives the
   value of this price cut, and takes on the value zero if no price cut
   was in effect.  The variable CUT is in dollars.
 
6.	Store id's 32, 33, 34, and 35 were dropped from the market 1 price files
   because of extremely low volume.
